Access `@tracked` properties in the template using `{{this.propertyName}}` syntax. The template automatically subscribes to these values and re-renders whenever they change. No special syntax needed beyond the standard Handlebars double-curly syntax.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class RunCounterComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;

  @action
  addRun() {
    this.runs = this.runs + 1;
  }

  <template>
    <p class="text-xl">Runs: {{this.runs}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.addRun}} class="btn">Add Run</button>
  </template>
}
```
Assign directly to the `@tracked` property using `this.propertyName = newValue`. This simple assignment triggers Glimmer's reactivity system and schedules a re-render. Always use `@action` on the method to ensure correct `this` binding when called from the template.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class WicketTrackerComponent extends Component {
  @tracked wickets = 0;

