Import `action` from `@ember/object` and place `@action` on the line immediately before the method definition. The `@action` decorator binds `this` correctly so that when the method is passed as an event handler in the template, it still refers to the component instance.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class BallCounterComponent extends Component {
  @tracked balls = 0;

  // Arrow function class field — this is auto-bound, no @action needed
  incrementBall = () => {
    this.balls = this.balls + 1;
  };

  <template>
    <p>Balls: {{this.balls}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.incrementBall}}>Ball</button>
  </template>
}
```
Arrow function class fields capture `this` lexically at definition time, so they are already correctly bound without `@action`. This is a valid alternative, but the `@action` decorator pattern is more conventional in Ember and makes intent clearer. Either approach works correctly.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreControlComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;
  @tracked extras = 0;

  @action
  addRun() {
    this.runs = this.runs + 1;
  }

  @action
  addWicket() {
    this.wickets = this.wickets + 1;
  }

  @action
  addExtra() {
    this.extras = this.extras + 1;
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.runs}}/{{this.wickets}} + {{this.extras}} extras</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.addRun}}>Run</button>
    <button {{on "click" this.addWicket}}>Wicket</button>
    <button {{on "click" this.addExtra}}>Extra</button>
  </template>
