```
Each `@action` method is decorated independently. There is no limit on the number of `@action` methods in a component. Each handles a specific user interaction, keeping the logic clean and focused.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class StrikeRateComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 54;
  @tracked balls = 40;

  get strikeRate() {
    if (this.balls === 0) return '0.00';
    return ((this.runs / this.balls) * 100).toFixed(2);
  }

  <template>
    <p>Strike Rate: {{this.strikeRate}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Native JavaScript getters automatically participate in Glimmer's autotracking. When the getter reads `this.runs` or `this.balls`, Glimmer registers those as dependencies. Whenever either `@tracked` property changes, the getter's result is recomputed and the template updates. No `@tracked` decorator is needed on the getter itself.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class MatchStatusComponent extends Component {
  @tracked isLive = true;
  @tracked runs = 145;
  @tracked wickets = 3;

