Glimmer tracks getter dependencies transitively. When `this.runs` changes, `strikeRate` is invalidated, which invalidates `strikeRateLabel` and `summary` too. All three update correctly in a single re-render. Chain getters freely — there is no performance penalty unless the computations are expensive (use `@cached` then).

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class LiveTickerComponent extends Component {
  @tracked intervalId = null;
  @tracked elapsedSeconds = 0;

  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args);
    this.intervalId = setInterval(() => {
      this.elapsedSeconds = this.elapsedSeconds + 1;
    }, 1000);
  }

  willDestroy() {
    super.willDestroy();
    if (this.intervalId) {
      clearInterval(this.intervalId);
      this.intervalId = null;
    }
  }

  <template>
    <p>Elapsed: {{this.elapsedSeconds}}s</p>
  </template>
}
```
Use `willDestroy()` to cancel timers, unsubscribe from events, or nullify references before the component is removed. Always call `super.willDestroy()` first. Avoid updating `@tracked` properties in `willDestroy` that would trigger rendering — the component is being torn down.

